The Ghanaian and Kenyan government has announced a ban for certain categories of persons coming to their countries, stating that all travels to their country is strongly discouraged until further notice. In an official statement issued yesterday and signed by a federal Minister, Kojo Oppong Nkrumah, the Ghanaian government stated that non-Ghanaian citizens who within last 14 days have travelled to countries with more than 200 confirmed COVID-19 cases are barred from Ghana. For Kenya, only Kenyan citizens and foreigners with valid resident permits will come in and proceed to self quarantine which takes effect in the next 48 hours,from the time of filling this report. While all day schools in Kenya will close on Monday, 16th March, 2020, boarding schools are to close by Wednesday 18th March. Apart from the ban, the Ghanaian government also urged travellers for a mandatory 14 day self quarantine upon entry to Ghana for residents and citizens traveling from these countries: China, Italy, Iran, South Korea, Spain, Germany, France, USA Switzerland, Norway, Sweden, Netherlands, Denmark, UK, Japan, Belgium and Austria. Others affected are: Qatar, Bahrain, Canada and Singapore. According to the statement, “any travel, except for Ghanaian citizens and persons with Ghana residence permits, who, within the last 14 days, has at least 200 cases of covid-19, will not be admitted into the Ghana jurisdiction”. It also instructed airlines not to allow such persons to embark,adding that border posts are instructed not to allow such persons into the jurisdiction of Ghana. In cases of any admissible traveller, who exhibits symptoms of Covid-19, such persons will be Quarantined and tested upon reaching Ghana. Enforcement, protocols, the Ghanaian statement noted, are being deployed in collaboration with state security and health authorities.